    <question>
        <prompt>Fundamentalism in the 1920s was characterized by:</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Acceptance of modern scientific theories</option>
            <option letter="b">Defense of traditional Protestant beliefs</option>
            <option letter="c">Support for social change</option>
            <option letter="d">Promotion of religious diversity</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>Fundamentalism in the 1920s was characterized by a strong defense of traditional Protestant beliefs against modernist challenges. Fundamentalists advocated literal interpretation of the Bible, opposed the teaching of evolution, and resisted changing social values. This religious movement represented a conservative reaction against modernization, scientific theories, and secular influences in American society.</explanation>
